        <strong>Magnesium Glycinate</strong>
        <p>Chelated with glycine, an inhibitory amino acid. Best for sleep and anxiety. Minimal GI side effects. Crosses the blood-brain barrier efficiently. The premium choice for nighttime use.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium Citrate</strong>
        <p>Bound to citric acid. Good bioavailability at approximately 25-30% absorption. Can cause loose stools at higher doses due to osmotic effect. Solid all-purpose form for daily supplementation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium Oxide</strong>
        <p>The cheapest form with only 4% bioavailability. Primarily acts as a laxative rather than a meaningful magnesium source. Avoid for sleep or recovery purposes despite high elemental magnesium content on the label.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium L-Threonate</strong>
        <p>The only form clinically shown to cross the blood-brain barrier and increase brain magnesium levels. Studied at MIT for cognitive function and memory. Expensive but promising for neurological applications.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2012 randomized controlled trial in the <em>Journal of Research in Medical Sciences</em> found that <strong>500mg of magnesium daily</strong> significantly improved sleep time, sleep efficiency, and melatonin concentration in elderly adults with insomnia, while reducing cortisol levels — the primary stress hormone that disrupts sleep architecture.</p>
