    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h3>Magnesium Forms Compared: Absorption, Side Effects, and Best Uses</h3>
      <p>The form of magnesium inside your gummy determines how much your body actually absorbs and whether you experience gastrointestinal side effects. Understanding these differences is essential for choosing the right product for your specific needs.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Glycinate / Bisglycinate</strong>
          <p>Bioavailability: High (chelated amino acid transport). Best for: Sleep, anxiety, muscle recovery. GI risk: Very low. The gold standard for nighttime magnesium supplementation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Citrate</strong>
          <p>Bioavailability: Good (25-30%). Best for: General supplementation, mild constipation relief. GI risk: Moderate at higher doses. Most common form in gummies due to favorable taste profile.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Oxide</strong>
          <p>Bioavailability: Poor (4%). Best for: Laxative effect only. GI risk: High. Despite high elemental magnesium content on the label, very little reaches systemic circulation. Not recommended for sleep.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>L-Threonate</strong>
          <p>Bioavailability: Moderate. Best for: Cognitive function, brain magnesium levels. GI risk: Low. The only form clinically shown to increase cerebrospinal magnesium. Currently rare in gummy format.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Practical dosing guide:</strong> The adult RDA is 310-320mg for women and 400-420mg for men. Most Americans get approximately 250mg from food, so a supplement providing 150-200mg of a bioavailable form is typically sufficient to close the gap. Exceeding 350mg from supplements alone (the Tolerable Upper Intake Level) increases the risk of diarrhea and cramping.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128214;</span>
        <p><strong>Related reading:</strong> For a deep dive into the science, read our complete guide to <a href="/blog/magnesium-for-sleep/">magnesium for sleep</a>, covering the best forms, optimal dosage, clinical evidence, and how magnesium compares to melatonin for long-term sleep improvement.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
        <p><strong>Label dose is not absorbed dose:</strong> A gummy listing 350mg of magnesium oxide delivers roughly 14mg of absorbed magnesium (4% bioavailability). A gummy listing 200mg of magnesium citrate delivers roughly 50-60mg of absorbed magnesium (25-30%). Always check the form, not just the milligram number on the front label.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

