    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Magnesium Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What type of magnesium is best for sleep?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium glycinate is widely considered the best form for sleep. Glycinate is an amino acid chelate that crosses the blood-brain barrier more efficiently than other forms and has a calming effect on the nervous system by binding to GABA receptors. Unlike magnesium citrate or oxide, glycinate does not cause gastrointestinal side effects at standard doses, making it ideal for nightly use. A 2012 study in the <em>Journal of Research in Medical Sciences</em> found that magnesium supplementation significantly improved sleep quality scores, sleep time, and melatonin concentration in elderly adults with insomnia.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much magnesium should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>The Recommended Dietary Allowance for magnesium is 310-320mg per day for adult women and 400-420mg per day for adult men. Most magnesium gummies provide 200-350mg per serving, designed to supplement dietary intake rather than replace it. The average American diet provides approximately 250mg from food, so a supplement in the 150-200mg range typically brings total intake close to the RDA. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level for supplemental magnesium is 350mg per day, above which GI side effects become more likely.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can magnesium gummies cause side effects?</summary>
      <p>The most common side effect is gastrointestinal discomfort, including loose stools, diarrhea, and stomach cramps. These effects are most common with magnesium citrate and oxide, which have an osmotic laxative effect in the intestines. Magnesium glycinate and bisglycinate are significantly less likely to cause GI issues because they are absorbed through amino acid transport pathways rather than osmotic mechanisms. Starting with a lower dose and taking magnesium with food can minimize side effects for any form.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between magnesium glycinate and citrate?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium glycinate is chelated with the amino acid glycine, providing a calming effect and superior absorption without GI side effects. It is the preferred form for sleep and anxiety support. Magnesium citrate is bound to citric acid, offering good absorption (25-30%) but with a known osmotic laxative effect at higher doses. Citrate is more appropriate for individuals seeking both magnesium supplementation and mild digestive regularity. Both forms are significantly better absorbed than magnesium oxide, which has a bioavailability of only 4%.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take magnesium gummies?</summary>
      <p>For sleep support, take magnesium gummies 30-60 minutes before bedtime. Magnesium activates the parasympathetic nervous system and helps regulate melatonin production, both of which facilitate sleep onset. For general supplementation, magnesium can be taken with any meal to improve absorption. Avoid taking magnesium at the same time as calcium supplements or high-dose zinc, as they compete for the same absorption pathways. Consistency matters more than precise timing for long-term magnesium status improvement.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do magnesium gummies actually work?</summary>
      <p>Yes, magnesium gummies can be effective if they contain a bioavailable form at an adequate dose. A 2017 systematic review in <em>Nutrients</em> analyzed 18 studies and concluded that magnesium supplementation significantly improved subjective measures of insomnia and sleep quality in adults with low baseline magnesium status. The key factor is the form used: glycinate and citrate are well-absorbed, while oxide has poor bioavailability of approximately 4%. Always verify the specific form and dose on the supplement facts panel.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is it safe to take magnesium every night?</summary>
      <p>For most healthy adults, taking magnesium nightly at or below the RDA is considered safe for long-term use. The National Institutes of Health classifies magnesium as a mineral with low toxicity risk in people with normal kidney function. Individuals with kidney disease should consult a physician before supplementing, as impaired kidneys cannot efficiently excrete excess magnesium. If you take medications such as antibiotics, bisphosphonates, or diuretics, check with your healthcare provider about potential interactions that may affect magnesium absorption or excretion.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are magnesium gummies better than pills?</summary>
      <p>Both delivery formats can provide comparable amounts of magnesium when properly formulated. Gummies offer advantages in compliance and taste, particularly for individuals who dislike swallowing large tablets. The trade-off is that gummies typically contain added sugar, flavoring, and coloring. Pills and capsules usually provide higher doses per serving with fewer inactive ingredients. For sleep support specifically, the gummy format has a practical advantage: the pleasant taste and chewing action create a positive bedtime routine association that reinforces consistent nightly use, which is the single most important factor in magnesium supplementation outcomes.</p>
    </details>

